{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"Events & Event Handling","slug":"js-events","subject":"JavaScript","category":"Web Development","level":"Intermediate","estimated_read_time":"15 mins","prerequisites":["DOM Introduction","Callbacks"],"learning_objectives":["What are Events? (click, submit, keydown)","Event Listeners (addEventListener)","Event Object (e.target)","Event Bubbling vs Capturing","Event Delegation"],"theory":"HTML events are \"things\" that happen to HTML elements (User clicks, Page loads).\nJavaScript can react to these events.\n\n*   `element.addEventListener(event, callback)`\n\n**Bubbling**: Event starts at target & goes UP to parents.\n**Capturing**: Event goes DOWN from root to target.","syntax":"button.addEventListener(\"click\", function(e) {\n  console.log(\"Clicked!\", e.target);\n});","examples":[{"code":"document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {\n  if (e.key === 'Escape') closeModal();\n});","output":"Runs function when Escape key is pressed.","explanation":"Global keyboard shortcuts."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Overwriting onclick property","correction":"`btn.onclick = func` overwrites previous listeners. `addEventListener` STACKS them (better).","example":""}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What is Event Delegation?","answer":"Adding a single listener to a parent element to manage events for all its children (using bubbling), instead of adding listeners to every child.","difficulty":"Important"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Prevent a form from submitting (reloading page).","hint":"e.preventDefault()","solution":"form.addEventListener('submit', e => e.preventDefault());","difficulty":"Easy"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Interactive Dashboards","description":"Drag and Drop, Hover effects, Click tracking all rely on Events.","code":""}],"exam_notes":["stopPropagation() stops bubbling.","preventDefault() stops default browser action (like link navigation)."],"summary":"Events make web pages interactive.","order":18}